<br>
To give you an idea, Point of Sale technology has been the only type of technology that these folks have taken on in the last decade and some still operate their businesses off of pen and paper and simple cash registers. Oddly enough, these clients run operations that can do well over a million dollars a year. They have been doing business the same way for over 50 years and have only recently come under pressure to change the way they do business.<br>
<br>
Has anyone out there had to help someone over come a fear of technology, perhaps a spouse or a parent? And how did you manage it? I am trying to get feedback from sources outside my industry so I can get a good perspective on this issue. <p><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-family:Arial;"> <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=220314" target="top">Kzan Verto</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->Giver of da Juice<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--> Member of <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.fireandfury.org" target="top">Fire and Fury</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.fireandfury.org/sigs/Kzan.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> </span><!--EZCODE FONT END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bajnok>Bajnok</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>...will gut you</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(11/26/03 5:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2151.topic&index=1>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Fear of technology, any ideas?</span><hr size=1> My father owns his own business. He is not exactly techno-phobic, but rather techno-ignorant about the majority of things out there and how they apply to his business.  My father is also an accountant by trade, and naturally pre-disposed to pencil and paper.  He's also very busy, so I often have to &quot;consult&quot; with him over the phone.  <br>
<br>
If I show him something, I need to be able to show two things to him:<br>
<br>
How will this save him time?<br>
<br>
How will this save him money?<br>
<br>
The key is to put it in simple terms, explain (simply) if there is a question, and show him the benefits of one way over another.  Teaching someone technology requires you to put it in their terms.  It doesn't matter if you understand it in your head, you need to get it in theirs.  They don't need to know what protocol you're using to communicate between offices, and they don't need to know what OS the server runs on.  But they do need to be told that an upgrade would allow them to do business from the back office too, instead of at the cash register.  Or from home.  Or from anywhere in the world.  And that the new software may take a while to learn, but they won't have to pour over papers at the end of the year come tax time.  Or they can do invoices at the click of a button, instead of by hand.<br>
<br>
Treat tech as a tool, like a hammer or drill.   That's always worked for me.  And keep it simple. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=661010" target="top">--<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Bajnok</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
